The student received a citation for Lot U2 without a valid permit. The student claims they were going to move their vehicle after seeing the sign, but their vehicle had stopped working by then. The student should be held fully accountable because it is their responsibility to be more aware of the parking regulations on campus in order to avoid a citation. Therefore, an $85 citation is upheld. In the future, the student is encouraged to submit further evidence supporting their claim through a second appeal.

From CRU: The student received a citation for improperly displaying their license plate in Lot 9b. The student claims they were running late for a very important class and so they parked the fastest and safest way. The student also claims they were not aware they had to keep their plate facing the parking lot. The student should be held fully accountable because it is their responsibility to give themself enough time to park in adherence to the parking regulations. Additionally, it is the student's responsibility to be aware of the parking regulations when they choose to bring a vehicle to campus. Therefore, the citation will be upheld.

From CRU: The student received a citation in Lot 19 for parking in an area other than their assigned area. The student claims they were informed that parking is free on the weekends for the upper levels in Lot 19. The student should be held fully accountable because it is their responsibility to be aware of the restrictions of the space their vehicle occupies. To clarify, the only parking spaces within Mowatt Lane Garage that are free over the weekends are spaces in Lot U2, not Lot 19 or metered spaces. In the future, the student is encouraged to double-check lot signage to ensure they are parking legally. Therefore, the citation is upheld.

From CRU: The student received an expired meter citation in the Xfinity Visitor Lot. The student claims they were cited while returning to their vehicle. The student should be held fully accountable because it is their responsibility to return to their vehicle within the allotted time that they paid for. In the future, the student could extend their metered time via ParkMobile if they know they are running late. Therefore, the citation is upheld.

From CRU: The student received a citation in Lot C1 for parking without a valid permit. The student claims it was their first day at school. The student will be held fully accountable because they have since paid this citation, thus assuming full responsibility for the violation. Therefore, the citation is upheld.

From CRU: The student received an expired meter citation at Regents Drive Garage. The student claims they were parked at 6 PM and were informed that Regents Garage is free after 4 PM. The student should be held fully accountable because it is their responsibility to be aware of the restrictions of the space their vehicle occupies. To clarify, only Lot B and Lot RR with Regents Drive Garage are unrestricted after 4 PM, not metered spaces. For further clarification, metered spaces have separate restrictions from surrounding lots and must be paid for daily from 7 AM to midnight. In the future, the student is encouraged to double-check the DOTS parking map for general parking information. Therefore, the citation is upheld.

The student received a citation in Lot C1 for parking without a valid permit. The student claims they were unable to acquire a parking pass, and construction makes it hard to find parking. The student also notes financial concerns. The student should be held fully accountable because they cannot park in restricted lots without a valid permit. In the future, the student is encouraged to contact DOTS customer service with questions or concerns regarding parking. Therefore, the citation is upheld.

From CRU: The student received an expired meter citation in the Stadium Drive garage. The student claims that this was the first time they parked. The student should be held fully accountable because this lot consists of all metered spaces, and they are required to pay for metered spots at all times. Therefore, a $45 citation is upheld.

The student received an expired meter citation near the Skinner Building. The student claims their class ran late, causing them to be late to their meter. The student should be held fully accountable because it is their responsibility to ensure their meter is paid for the entirety of their parked time. In the future, the student is encouraged to park in nearby metered spaces with the ability to extend their meter time via the Park Mobile app. Therefore, the citation is upheld.

The student received an expired meter citation near Elkton Hall. The student claims they parked during free hours. The student should be held fully accountable because they parked in a metered space without paying during enforced hours (daily, 7 am-midnight). In the future, the student could refer to the DOTS website to receive further metered parking guidance. Therefore, the citation is upheld.

From CRU: The student received an expired meter citation at Mowatt Lane Garage. The student claims their mother parked their car in the incorrect spot because they were unaware of the parking rules. The student should be held fully accountable because it is their responsibility to ensure their vehicle is legally parked on campus, and CRU research indicates they were parked in the metered space outside their paid timeframe. To clarify, metered parking must be paid daily from 7 AM to Midnight. Therefore, the citation is upheld.

From CRU: The student received an expired meter citation at Mowatt Lane Garage. The student claims their mother parked their car in the incorrect spot because they were unaware of the parking rules. The student should be held fully accountable because it is their responsibility to ensure their vehicle is legally parked on campus, and CRU research indicates they were parked outside of their paid timeframe. Therefore, the citation is upheld.

From CRU: The student received an expired meter citation at Mowatt Lane Garage. The student claims their mother parked their car in the incorrect spot because they were unaware of the parking rules. The student should be held fully accountable because it is their responsibility to ensure their vehicle is legally parked on campus, and they must pay for metered parking during enforced hours. Therefore, the citation is upheld.

The student received a citation in Lot 9b without a valid permit. The student claims they weren't given proper orientation about the parking regulations. The student should be held fully accountable because they cannot park in Lot 9b during enforced hours without a permit. The student is encouraged to contact DOTS customer service about obtaining a permit. Therefore, the citation is upheld.

The student received a citation in Lot 11b without a valid permit. The student claims they weren't given proper orientation about the parking regulations and have no one to drop them off at campus. The student also notes financial concerns. The student should be held fully accountable because Lot 11b requires a valid permit during enforced hours. Therefore, the citation is upheld. In the future, the student is encouraged to contact DOTS about potential parking accommodations.

The student received a citation in Lot M for parking in an area other than their assigned area. The student claims they were under the impression that after work hours, they were allowed to park anywhere on campus. The student should be held fully accountable because it is their responsibility to ensure they are aware of the restrictions of the lots their vehicle occupies. In the future, the student is encouraged to double-check the DOTS parking map and lot signage to ensure legal parking. Therefore, the citation is upheld.

The student claims they should be able to park in those areas 24/7 because they have permits for Lots U2 and 4b. The student should be held accountable because they cannot park overnight in non-overnight parking lots, such as Lot 4b, and it is their responsibility to be aware of lot restrictions. However, the student should be granted some leniency because it is their first citation. In the future, the student is encouraged to double-check the DOTS website for information on overnight parking. Therefore, the citation is reduced.

From CRU: The student received a citation in Lot 1c for parking multiple vehicles at once with one permit. The student claims they recently sold one of their vehicles but both parties forgot to update their parking accounts accordingly. The student will be granted full leniency because although they did not supply any evidence to support their claim, CRU research shows that the vehicle was removed from the appellant's account shortly before submitting the related appeals. As such, while not definitive, it could be taken to support the student's submitted claim. It should be noted that the new owner of the vehicle referenced as 'sold' did not have a permit to park in this lot at the time of the citation. Therefore, this citation is voided.
